Z", "properties": [{"name": "policyVersion", "type": "string", "description": "Version identifier for the applied SoD policy or rule set."}, {"name": "lastAuditDate", "type": "date", "description": "Date of the most recent audit or review of SoD compliance."}, {"name": "violationAlertLevel", "type": "enum", "description": "Severity or priority of alerts triggered by SoD violations (e.g., Low, Medium, High)."}], "description": "SoD, or Segregation of Duties, is a fundamental risk management and internal control principle designed to prevent fraud, errors, and conflicts of interest in financial services operations. By ensuring that no single individual has full control over critical financial transactions or processes, SoD reduces the likelihood of unauthorized activities and improves accountability. In the context of financial services, typical SoD implementations include separating roles for transaction initiation, review, and approval, such as ensuring that the person who sets up a payment isn''t the one to authorize it. It also applies in trading, settlement, custody, and compliance functions where independent checks are required. Proper SoD implementation is essential for effective oversight and safeguarding of assets.", "relationships": [{"type": "depends_on", "label": "SoD enforcement relies on compliance check outcomes", "targetId": "fibo-17"}, {"type": "related", "label": "SoD is applied to distinct roles in the trade settlement process", "targetId": "fibo-10"}, {"type": "related", "label": "SoD is critical in payment instruction approval workflows", "targetId": "fibo-12"}, {"type": "related", "label": "Segregation of Duties (SoD) is a critical component in compliance checks to ensure that no individual has control over conflicting duties.", "targetId": "Compliance Check"}, {"type": "related", "label": "SoD principles help to enhance transaction monitoring by ensuring that no single individual is responsible for all aspects of a transaction.", "targetId": "Tr